,"id":"42070"},{"type":"contributions","id":"44028"},{"type":"contributions","id":"44860"}]}},"meta":{"canRevise":false,"canManage":false,"canDelete":false}},{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"103248","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionRevisions/103248"},"attributes":{"stem":"\u003Cp\u003EA 12-year-old boy presents to the Emergency Department with recurrent generalised tonic-clonic seizures that started earlier that morning. He has been unwell with fever and headaches for the past week, which his parents had been treating with paracetamol. He has a medical history of asthma and recurrent otitis media. His only regular medication is salbutamol inhaler as needed.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EOn examination, he appears unwell. His pulse rate is 110/min, blood pressure 115/70 mmHg, respiratory rate 22/min, SpO2 98% on room air, and temperature 38.8\u00b0C. The left tympanic membrane is erythematous and bulging. There is tenderness over the left mastoid process. Neurological examination is limited by post-ictal drowsiness. A CT brain is performed (Image).\u003C/p\u003E","stemQuestion":"Which one of the following is the most likely underlying cause for his presentation?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["Malignancy","Mastoiditis","Trauma","Encephalitis","Intracerebral haemorrhage"],"correctOptions":[1],"correctResponses":null,"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003EThis patient presents with new onset seizures, fever, and headache. The CT brain demonstrates a ring-enhancing lesion in the temporal lobe, which is highly suggestive of an intracerebral abscess. Given the history of recurrent otitis media and examination findings of mastoid tenderness, \u003Cstrong\u003Emastoiditis\u003C/strong\u003E is the most likely underlying cause.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EMalignancy\u003C/strong\u003E can present with ring-enhancing lesions on CT, but the acute onset of symptoms and presence of systemic features of infection make this less likely. Primary brain tumours typically have a more insidious onset.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EThere is no history of \u003Cstrong\u003Etrauma\u003C/strong\u003E to explain this presentation. While contusions can appear as ring-enhancing lesions, they would be expected to have corresponding trauma history.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EEncephalitis\u003C/strong\u003E typically presents with more diffuse brain involvement on CT rather than a focal ring-enhancing lesion. While it can cause seizures and fever, the imaging findings are not consistent.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EIntracerebral haemorrhage\u003C/strong\u003E would have different imaging characteristics on CT and would not typically present with fever unless there was secondary infection.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EMastoiditis is a serious complication of chronic suppurative otitis media that can lead to intracranial spread of infection. The temporal location of the abscess is typical for spread from mastoid air cells. Management involves urgent neurosurgical intervention and intravenous antibiotics.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":null,"learningPoints":["Temporal lobe abscesses in children are most commonly caused by mastoiditis as a complication of chronic suppurative otitis media.","Ring-enhancing lesions on CT brain can be caused by abscess, malignancy, subacute infarct, or contusion.","New onset seizures with fever and headache should prompt urgent neuroimaging."],"references":["Shahzad K et al. Brain abscess in children. Journal of the College of Physicians and Surgeons. 2005,15(10):609-11. Available at: https://pubmed.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/18518751/","Cassano P, Ciprandi G, Passali D. Acute mastoiditis in children. Acta Biomed. 2020 Feb 17;91(1-S):54-59. Available at: https://pmc.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/articles/PMC7947742/"]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"85666"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"383"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[{"type":"media","id":"18473"}]},"explanationMedia":{"data":[]}}},{"type":"media","id":"18473","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/media/18473"},"attributes":{"mimeType":"image/jpeg","url":"https://app.emedici.com/storage/media/7da9fb26-91e9-4a39-a047-7953a7ce0f40.jpg","thumbUrl":"https://app.emedici.com/storage/media/7da9fb26-91e9-4a39-a047-7953a7ce0f40.jpg","isProcessed":true,"width":286,"height":318}},{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"85666","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/itemRevisions/85666"},"attributes":{"createdAt":"2025-05-20T21:10:55+09:30","updatedAt":"2025-05-20T21:11:38+09:30"},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"383"}},"content":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"103248"}}},"meta":{"canDelete":false}},{"type":"tags","id":"9","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/9"},"attributes":{"emoji":"\ud83d\udc76","name":"Paediatrics","synonyms":[],"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":"2024-01-16T08:39:03+10:30"},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"1"}},"heading":{"data":{"type":"tagHeadings","id":"1"}}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"14","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/14"},"attributes":{"emoji":"\ud83e\udda0","name":"Infectious Diseases","synonyms":["ID"],"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":"2021-05-21T07:51:58+09:30"},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"1"}},"heading":{"data":{"type":"tagHeadings","id":"1"}}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"24","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/24"},"attributes":{"emoji":"\ud83d\ude91","name":"Emergency Medicine","synonyms":null,"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"1"}},"heading":{"data":{"type":"tagHeadings","id":"5"}}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"32","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/32"},"attributes":{"emoji":